The graph of $x^2 - 2xy + 3y^2 = 5$ is an ellipse, although its axes are not parallel to the coordinate axes. Two horizontal lines and two vertical lines lie tangent to the ellipse, forming a rectangle, as shown:
[asy]
size(7cm);
draw(rotate(20)*xscale(2.4)*unitcircle);
draw((-3.5,0)--(3.5,0),EndArrow);
draw((0,-2.5)--(0,2.5),EndArrow);
real r1=2.29; draw((r1,-2.2)--(r1,2.2),dotted);
draw((-r1,-2.2)--(-r1,2.2),dotted);
real r2=1.26; draw((-3,r2)--(3,r2),dotted);
draw((-3,-r2)--(3,-r2),dotted);
label("$x$",(3.5,0),E); label("$y$",(0,2.5),N);
[/asy]
What is the area of the rectangle?

inference:
The center of the ellipse is at the origin.  Let the vertices of the rectangle be $(\pm a,b)$ and $(\pm a,-b).$  Then the distance between the vertical lines is $2a,$ and the distance between the horizontal lines is $2b.$  The area of the rectangle is $4ab.$

[asy]
size(7cm);
draw(rotate(20)*xscale(2.4)*unitcircle);
draw((-3.5,0)--(3.5,0),EndArrow);
draw((0,-2.5)--(0,2.5),EndArrow);
real r1=2.29; draw((r1,-2.2)--(r1,2.2),dotted);
draw((-r1,-2.2)--(-r1,2.2),dotted);
real r2=1.26; draw((-3,r2)--(3,r2),dotted);
draw((-3,-r2)--(3,-r2),dotted);
label("$x$",(3.5,0),E); label("$y$",(0,2.5),N);
draw((-r1,r2)--(r1,r2)-- (r1,-r2)--(-r1,-r2)--cycle);
label("$(a,b)$",(r1,r2),NE);
label("$(-a,b)$",(-r1,r2),NW);
label("$(a,-b)$",(r1,-r2),SE);
label("$(-a,-b)$",(-r1,-r2),SW);
[/asy]

The points $(\pm a,b)$ and $(\pm a,-b)$ lie on the ellipse, so
\begin{align*}
a^2 - 2ab + 3b^2 &= 5, \\
a^2 + 2ab + 3b^2 &= 5.
\end{align*}Adding these equations, we get $2a^2 + 6b^2 = 10,$ so $a^2 + 3b^2 = 5.$

Subtracting the equations, we get $-4ab = 0,$ so $ab = 0.$  Since $a$ and $b$ are nonzero, this is a contradiction.  Therefore, there is no such rectangle, and the area is $\boxed{0}.$

